node.text:
What did you learn from this quote?

Tag 4 friends who needs to read it!
___________________________________
To me, this quote embodies a mindset of gratitude. So often we go through life without acknowledging the blessings that are around us because they are merely there by circumstance.

• We take these things for granted, but when we take responsibility for these elements, and become more mindful of the processes that provide it for us, we start to realize how lucky we really are.

• By carrying the weight of the task, and experiencing for yourself the effort required to produce the result, you’ll develop a new level of respect for everything that goes into it.

• It is essential to understand that once you carry your own water, you will be learning the cost of every drop. You are able to apprehend the value of money only when you earn it. In the same way, we understand the value of food and water only when we have to go out and toil for the whole day.

In the same way, we often ignore a lot of things in our lives and we get to understand their true value only when we have to go through the tremendous labor in earning it.

Nothing comes easy, not even water. We keep our tap opened, all throughout the day. However, we fail to understand that each and everything is hard to get, and we learn the value of each and every drop only when we ourselves bear the same.

Repost @_dailyvocabulary

"It's" is a contraction, meaning a shorter or "contracted" form of "it is" or "it has." (Example: It's going to rain.)

"Its" is a possessive pronoun meaning, "belonging to it," or a "quality of it" (Example: The carrier lost its license) or (Example: Its color is red.)

Follow 👉@theenglishacademy_sg 

These rules seem simple, but sometimes cause pain. That's because when most English speakers want to show possession, they add an " ’s " as in "We took the pilot's license."

SO REMEMBER: 
It’s is a contraction of “it is” or “it has.” Its is a possessive determiner we use to say that something belongs to or refers to something.
